The following is an example of how to automatically generate a table of contents (TOC) in a LATEX document using the hyperref package:

First, we will create a section of our document that contains the TOC. This section will be named "TOC":

```
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{hyperref}
\begin{document}
\section*{TOC}
```

Next, we will insert the TOC. In this example, the TOC will be inserted in the first page. However, you can insert it anywhere in your document by changing the page number in the code below:

```
\begin{toc}[H]
\clearpage

\addcontentsline{toc}{chapter}{Table of Contents}
\addcontentsline{toc}{chapter}{Preface}
\addcontentsline{toc}{chapter}{Acknowledgements}
\addcontentsline{toc}{chapter}{Introduction}
\addcontentsline{toc}{chapter}{Introduction to Formal Language Theory}
\addcontentsline{toc}{chapter}{Introduction to Formal Language Theory (contd.)}

% You can skip some of the pages in your TOC if they are empty.
% This is useful if you have a large document and want to have a shorter TOC.

\cleardoublepage
```

Notice that the TOC is generated in a separate section called "TOC". In this section, there are three separate commands that generate different parts of the TOC:

- `\addcontentsline`: This command inserts a new line into the TOC and adds the heading "Table of Contents". You can change this heading by replacing "Table of Contents" with your own heading.

- `\clearpage`: This command skips a page break in the TOC so that all pages are listed in a single list. This command is useful if you have many pages in your TOC and want to skip some of them to make the table more compact.

- `\addcontentsline`: This command inserts new lines into the TOC and adds new headings for each section. You can change this heading by replacing "Preface" with your own heading.

